@node "coordinate" "Coordinate"
Simple. Defines a point.


  Attributes

  x,
  y,
  z


  Methods


      rotate(angle,coordinate=NIL)

  Rotates the point by the given angle around the given coordinate. If the
  second parameter is omitted, the point is rotated around 0;0;0. This method
  exists for all three axisses(?): rotateX(), rotateY() and rotateZ()

      mirror(list)

  'Mirrors' the point either at (0;0;0) or a given coordinate.
  NIY

  shift(coordinate)

  Shifts itself by the given coordinate.

      neg()

  x,y, and z are negated.

      get/setX(), get/setY(), get/setZ()

  Return the value of the according attribute or set it, respectively.

      copy(coordinate)

  Copies its attributes to the argument.
@endnode

@node "line" "Line"
Defines a line.

  Attributes

  start:coordinate
  end:coordinate


  Methods


  length()

  Returns the length of the line.


  NOTE: the inherited methods just call the method for every coordinate.
@endnode

@node "vector" "Vector"
A vector begins at a point and has a direction and a length. The direction is
defined by angles to the x,y and z axis.

         .
      y /|\
         |
         |
         |_____\ x
         /     /
        /
    z |/_



  Attributes

  start:coordinate
  x:angle (?)
  y:angle (?)
  z:angle (?)
  length:fraction(?)


  Methods (tricky:)

  The mathematical methods have to be redefined and extended.

  Add(whereto)

  [simple] Just puts itself after whereto.

  Sub(whatfrom)

  Removes itself from whatfrom.

  Mul(withwhat)

  Multiplicates itself with the other vector. Note that we will have two
  versions of this method, one returning a number and one returning a vector
  (I love it).

  Div(bywhat)

  Yes.

  Exp(exponent)

  Interesting. May be tricky - two versions?
@endnode

@node "polyline" "Polyline"
This is a string of lines. Take a rectangle and remove one side - the result
is a polyline consisting of three lines or four points.

  Attributes

  coordinate: list of n-coordinates


  Methods

  The methods of Coordinate just map themselves on every coordinate of the
  list.

  several getXxx() methods:

  getMiddle()
  getHight()
  getWidth()
  getDepth()
  getHighest() &opposit
  getFrontmost() &opposit
  getRightmost() &opposit
  getLength()
  getArea() (?)
  getVolume() (?)

  stretchX() by absolute value or percent
  stretchY()
  stretchZ()
@endnode

@node "area" "Area"
An area is built with some lines as borders.


  Methods

  The methods just map the Line's methods on each line.
@endnode

